<subSubSection pageId="75" pageNumber="76" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="75.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,259,285]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hechtel" authorityYear="1965" box="[322,523,259,285]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Geodia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gibberosa">
<emphasis box="[322,523,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Geodia gibberosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been shown to be a species complex based on molecular phylogenetic analysis (
<bibRefCitation author="Cardenas, P. &amp; Xavier, J. A. &amp; Reveillaud, J. &amp; Schander, C. &amp; Rapp, H. T." box="[195,432,295,321]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" pagination="18318" refId="ref74822" refString="Cardenas, P., Xavier, J. A., Reveillaud, J., Schander, C. &amp; Rapp, H. T. (2011) Molecular phylogeny of the Astrophorida (Porifera, Demospongiae) reveals an unexpected hight level of spicule homoplasy. PLoS ONE, 6 (4), e 18318. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0018318" type="journal article" year="2011">
Cárdenas 
<emphasis box="[309,365,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
). The same results have been suggested in morphological analysis (
<bibRefCitation author="Cardenas, P. &amp; Menegola, C. &amp; Rapp, H. T. &amp; Diaz, M. C." box="[1187,1425,295,321]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" pagination="1 - 39" refId="ref74746" refString="Cardenas, P., Menegola, C., Rapp, H. T. &amp; Diaz, M. C. (2009) Morphological description and DNA barcodes of shallow-water Tetractinellida (Porifera: Demospongiae) from Bocas del Toro, Panama, with description of a new species. Zootaxa, 2276 (1), 1 - 39. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2276.1.1" type="journal article" year="2009">
Cárdenas 
<emphasis box="[1301,1357,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
). However, Cárdenas et al.’s (2011; 
<figureCitation box="[545,642,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1978,2002]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1425,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-325@8.[151,1435,1425,1954]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 2. Agelas clathrodes (Schmidt, 1870) (CNPGG-2297), skeleton and spicules:A. transversal section of the skeleton; B. detail of the ectosomal region, upper side; C. verticillated acanthostyles. Scale bars: A = 500 µm; B = 100 µm; C = 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5454384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5454384/files/figure.png" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Figure 2</figureCitation>
) results have shown that a specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[1133,1219,331,357]" name="Mexico" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Mexico</collectingCountry>
is sister to another from 
<collectingCountry box="[211,286,367,393]" name="Belize" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Belize</collectingCountry>
. There are essential morphological differences in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hechtel" authorityYear="1965" box="[833,977,367,393]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Geodia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gibberosa">
<emphasis box="[833,977,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">G. gibberosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on morphological analysis (
<bibRefCitation author="Cardenas, P. &amp; Menegola, C. &amp; Rapp, H. T. &amp; Diaz, M. C." pageId="75" pageNumber="76" pagination="1 - 39" refId="ref74746" refString="Cardenas, P., Menegola, C., Rapp, H. T. &amp; Diaz, M. C. (2009) Morphological description and DNA barcodes of shallow-water Tetractinellida (Porifera: Demospongiae) from Bocas del Toro, Panama, with description of a new species. Zootaxa, 2276 (1), 1 - 39. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2276.1.1" type="journal article" year="2009">
Cárdenas 
<emphasis box="[194,249,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
), this is shown in a particular specimen from Florida with more regular gross morphology and smaller sterrasters with a different rosette pattern (op.cit. details therein).Another morphological observation of 
<bibRefCitation author="Cardenas, P. &amp; Menegola, C. &amp; Rapp, H. T. &amp; Diaz, M. C." pageId="75" pageNumber="76" pagination="1 - 39" refId="ref74746" refString="Cardenas, P., Menegola, C., Rapp, H. T. &amp; Diaz, M. C. (2009) Morphological description and DNA barcodes of shallow-water Tetractinellida (Porifera: Demospongiae) from Bocas del Toro, Panama, with description of a new species. Zootaxa, 2276 (1), 1 - 39. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2276.1.1" type="journal article" year="2009">
Cárdenas 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">et al.</emphasis>
(2009)
</bibRefCitation>
was the presence of anatriaenes in a Panamanian individual, but this latter character is questioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="van Soest, R. W. M." pageId="75" pageNumber="76" pagination="1 - 225" refId="ref81605" refString="van Soest, R. W. M. (2017) Sponges of the Guyana Shelf. Zootaxa, 4217 (1), 1 - 225. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4217.1.1" type="journal article" year="2017">van Soest (2017)</bibRefCitation>
, who mentions that the 
<typeStatus box="[567,665,511,537]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">holotype</typeStatus>
lacks anatriaenes. Tetractine spines were also rare in the material of 
<bibRefCitation author="Cardenas, P. &amp; Menegola, C. &amp; Rapp, H. T. &amp; Diaz, M. C." box="[151,403,547,573]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" pagination="1 - 39" refId="ref74746" refString="Cardenas, P., Menegola, C., Rapp, H. T. &amp; Diaz, M. C. (2009) Morphological description and DNA barcodes of shallow-water Tetractinellida (Porifera: Demospongiae) from Bocas del Toro, Panama, with description of a new species. Zootaxa, 2276 (1), 1 - 39. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2276.1.1" type="journal article" year="2009">
Cárdenas 
<emphasis box="[262,319,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">et al.</emphasis>
(2009)
</bibRefCitation>
. Our specimens have a massive habit and absent anatriaenes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="75.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hechtel" authorityYear="1965" box="[199,399,583,609]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Geodia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gibberosa">
<emphasis box="[199,399,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Geodia gibberosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in tropical and subtropical areas of the West Atlantic, from 
<collectingRegion country="United States of America" name="North Carolina" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">North Carolina</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[209,263,619,645]" name="United States of America" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">USA</collectingCountry>
(
<geoCoordinate box="[282,353,618,645]" degrees="35" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" precision="55555" value="35.0">35° N</geoCoordinate>
) to 
<collectingCountry box="[401,469,619,645]" name="Brazil" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<geoCoordinate box="[487,552,618,645]" degrees="25" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" precision="55555" value="-25.0">25° S</geoCoordinate>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Muricy, G. &amp; Lopes, D. A. &amp; Hajdu, E. &amp; Carvalho, M. D. S. &amp; Moraes, F. C. &amp; Klautau, M. &amp; Menegola, C. &amp; Pinheiro, U." box="[578,799,619,645]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" refId="ref79280" refString="Muricy, G., Lopes, D. A., Hajdu, E., Carvalho, M. D. S., Moraes, F. C., Klautau, M., Menegola, C. &amp; Pinheiro, U. (2011) Catalogue of Brazilian Porifera. Serie livros 46. Museu Nacional, Rio de Janeiro, 300 pp." type="book" year="2011">
Muricy 
<emphasis box="[671,723,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">et al</emphasis>
. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
). In the GoM, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hechtel" authorityYear="1965" box="[971,1118,619,645]" class="Demospongiae" family="Geodiidae" genus="Geodia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gibberosa">
<emphasis box="[971,1118,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">G. gibberosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reported from the northern (
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt, O." box="[259,417,655,681]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" refId="ref81219" refString="Schmidt, O. (1870) Grundzuge einer Spongien-Fauna des atlantischen Gebietes. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig, 88 pp., VI pls." type="book" year="1870">Schmidt 1870</bibRefCitation>
) and the southern region (
<bibRefCitation author="Topsent, E." box="[705,860,655,681]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" pagination="30 - 52" refId="ref82452" refString="Topsent, E. (1889) Quelques spongiaires du Banc de Campeche et de la Pointe-a-Pitre. Memoires de la Societe zoologique de France, 2, 30 - 52." type="journal article" year="1889">Topsent 1889</bibRefCitation>
; present work). In the SGoM the species is common in coral reefs.
</paragraph>
